hands_on_practices.problem:
Let $\mathbb{Q}$ denote the set of all rational numbers. Consider the function $f: \mathbb{R} \to \mathbb{R}$ defined as
$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
(x-\sqrt{2})^2  \text{if } x \in \mathbb{Q} \\
0  \text{if } x \notin \mathbb{Q}
\end{cases}
$$
It can be shown that this function is differentiable at exactly one point in its domain. Determine this unique real number $x_0$ where $f$ is differentiable.
